+\subsection{Research Track: Minimal Relational Link--Field Action}
+\label{sec:rt_minimal_link_field_action}
+%======================================================================
+
+\subsubsection{Status and objective}
+
+\textbf{[RESEARCH-TRACK / CANON CANDIDATE].}
+The purpose of this section is to replace the ambiguous statement that a photon
+is ``local rotation of the medium'' by a sharper microscopic hypothesis:
+material rotation belongs to the site or vortex sector, whereas radiative
+torsion belongs to oriented connections between neighbouring \AE ther elements.
+The action below is the minimal local, parity-even, conservative, Abelian model
+that realizes this distinction.  It is a model-selection hypothesis, not yet a
+derivation from a completed \AE ther microphysics.
+
+\subsubsection{Discrete relational variables}
+
+Let the microscopic adjacency structure be an oriented cellular graph
+\begin{align}
+    \mathcal G=(V,E,P),
+\end{align}
+with sites $i\in V$, oriented links $e=(i\!\to\!j)\in E$, elementary
+plaquettes $p\in P$, and characteristic link spacing $a_\ell$.  Assign to each
+oriented link a compact relative torsion phase
+\begin{align}
+    U_e=e^{i\vartheta_e}\in U(1),
+    \qquad
+    \vartheta_{\bar e}=-\vartheta_e\pmod{2\pi}.
+    \label{eq:rt_link_compact_phase}
+\end{align}
+The compact $U(1)$ choice is the minimal hypothesis when relative torsion is a
+periodic phase.  A noncompact real link field is recovered by linearizing around
+one phase branch.
+
+Introduce a site variable $\phi_i(T)$ only as a temporal connection or Lagrange
+multiplier.  It is not the physical angular velocity of the \AE ther element and
+carries no independent site-rotation kinetic term.  Under a local change of
+phase zero,
+\begin{align}
+    \vartheta_{ij}
+    &\mapsto
+    \vartheta_{ij}+\chi_j-\chi_i,
+    \\
+    \phi_i
+    &\mapsto
+    \phi_i-\dot\chi_i,
+    \label{eq:rt_link_gauge_transformation}
+\end{align}
+the gauge-invariant link twist rate and plaquette holonomy are
+\begin{align}
+    \mathscr E_{ij}
+    &:=-\dot\vartheta_{ij}-(\phi_j-\phi_i),
+    \label{eq:rt_link_electric_variable}
+    \\
+    \mathscr B_p
+    &:={\sum}_{e\in\partial p}s_{pe}\vartheta_e
+    \pmod{2\pi},
+    \label{eq:rt_link_plaquette_holonomy}
+\end{align}
+where $s_{pe}=\pm1$ records relative orientation.
+
+\subsubsection{Minimal compact link action}
+
+The proposed source-free microscopic action is
+\begin{align}
+    S_{\rm link}^{\rm lat}
+    =
+    \int dT\,
+    \left[
+        \frac{I_\ell}{2}
+        \sum_{e\in E}\mathscr E_e^2
+        -
+        K_\ell
+        \sum_{p\in P}
+        \left(1-\cos\mathscr B_p\right)
+    \right],
+    \label{eq:rt_minimal_compact_link_action}
+\end{align}
+with
+\begin{align}
+    I_\ell>0,
+    \qquad
+    K_\ell>0,
+    \qquad
+    [I_\ell]=\mathrm{kg\,m^2},
+    \qquad
+    [K_\ell]=\mathrm{J}.
+    \label{eq:rt_link_parameter_dimensions}
+\end{align}
+Here $I_\ell$ is a link inertia and $K_\ell$ is a plaquette torsional energy
+scale.  No value of $c$, $e$, $m_e$, $h$, $\varepsilon_0$, or $\mu_0$ occurs in
+Eq.~\eqref{eq:rt_minimal_compact_link_action}.
+
+Variation with respect to $\phi_i$ gives the source-free discrete Gauss
+constraint
+\begin{align}
+    \sum_{e\ni i}s_{ie}\,I_\ell\mathscr E_e=0.
+    \label{eq:rt_link_discrete_gauss}
+\end{align}
+Variation with respect to an oriented link gives, up to the declared orientation
+convention,
+\begin{align}
+    I_\ell\dot{\mathscr E}_e
+    =
+    K_\ell
+    \sum_{p\supset e}s_{pe}\sin\mathscr B_p.
+    \label{eq:rt_link_discrete_ampere}
+\end{align}
+Equations~\eqref{eq:rt_link_discrete_gauss}--
+\eqref{eq:rt_link_discrete_ampere} evolve link torsion without introducing a
+net site-spin degree of freedom.
+
+\subsubsection{Linear spectrum and emergent causal speed}
+
+For $|\mathscr B_p|\ll1$, the compact potential becomes quadratic.  On a
+regular isotropic cubic complex, after gauge fixing and projection onto either
+transverse polarization, the linear branch satisfies
+\begin{align}
+    \omega^2(\mathbf k)
+    =
+    \frac{4K_\ell}{I_\ell}
+    \sum_{a=1}^{3}
+    \sin^2\!\left(\frac{k_a a_\ell}{2}\right).
+    \label{eq:rt_link_lattice_dispersion}
+\end{align}
+Therefore, for $|\mathbf k|a_\ell\ll1$,
+\begin{align}
+    \omega^2
+    =
+    c_T^2|\mathbf k|^2
+    +O\!\left(a_\ell^4|\mathbf k|^4\right),
+    \qquad
+    \boxed{
+    c_T=a_\ell\sqrt{\frac{K_\ell}{I_\ell}}
+    }.
+    \label{eq:rt_link_emergent_speed}
+\end{align}
+Equation~\eqref{eq:rt_link_emergent_speed} is the first zero-legacy speed target:
+$c_T$ is generated by a relation stiffness divided by a relation inertia.  The
+operational identification $c_T=c$ is tested only after $a_\ell$, $I_\ell$, and
+$K_\ell$ have been determined independently.
+
+\subsubsection{Continuum limit and Maxwell--Faraday structure}
+
+Write, on a regular branch,
+\begin{align}
+    \vartheta_{i,a}
+    =
+    a_\ell\mathcal A_{\ell,a}(\mathbf x_i,T)
+    +O(a_\ell^2),
+    \qquad
+    \phi_i=\Phi_\ell(\mathbf x_i,T).
+\end{align}
+Define
+\begin{align}
+    \boldsymbol{\mathcal E}_\ell
+    &:=-\partial_T\boldsymbol{\mathcal A}_\ell-\nabla\Phi_\ell,
+    \\
+    \boldsymbol{\mathcal B}_\ell
+    &:=\nabla\times\boldsymbol{\mathcal A}_\ell.
+    \label{eq:rt_link_continuum_fields}
+\end{align}
+Up to cell-shape and coordination factors, the infrared action is
+\begin{align}
+    S_{\rm link}^{\rm IR}
+    =
+    \int dT\,d^3x
+    \left[
+        \frac{\epsilon_\ell}{2}
+        |\boldsymbol{\mathcal E}_\ell|^2
+        -
+        \frac{1}{2\mu_\ell}
+        |\boldsymbol{\mathcal B}_\ell|^2
+    \right],
+    \label{eq:rt_link_continuum_action}
+\end{align}
+where
+\begin{align}
+    \epsilon_\ell
+    \simeq
+    \frac{I_\ell}{a_\ell},
+    \qquad
+    \mu_\ell^{-1}
+    \simeq
+    K_\ell a_\ell,
+    \qquad
+    \frac{1}{\epsilon_\ell\mu_\ell}
+    =c_T^2.
+    \label{eq:rt_link_continuum_coefficients}
+\end{align}
+The symbols $\epsilon_\ell$ and $\mu_\ell$ are SST link-response coefficients;
+they are not inserted as the measured electromagnetic constants
+$\varepsilon_0$ and $\mu_0$.
+
+With
+\begin{align}
+    \boldsymbol{\mathcal D}_\ell
+    :=\epsilon_\ell\boldsymbol{\mathcal E}_\ell,
+    \qquad
+    \boldsymbol{\mathcal H}_\ell
+    :=\mu_\ell^{-1}\boldsymbol{\mathcal B}_\ell,
+\end{align}
+variation and the definitions in Eq.~\eqref{eq:rt_link_continuum_fields} give
+\begin{align}
+    \nabla\cdot\boldsymbol{\mathcal D}_\ell&=0,
+    &
+    \nabla\times\boldsymbol{\mathcal H}_\ell
+    -\partial_T\boldsymbol{\mathcal D}_\ell&=0,
+    \\
+    \nabla\cdot\boldsymbol{\mathcal B}_\ell&=0,
+    &
+    \nabla\times\boldsymbol{\mathcal E}_\ell
+    +\partial_T\boldsymbol{\mathcal B}_\ell&=0.
+    \label{eq:rt_link_source_free_maxwell_structure}
+\end{align}
+Thus the source-free Maxwell--Faraday form is an infrared consequence of the
+minimal link action.  This is a structural isomorphism, not yet a proof that the
+SST fields equal the experimentally normalized electromagnetic fields.
+
+Gauge invariance removes a physical longitudinal connection mode and forbids a
+bare mass term $m_A^2|\boldsymbol{\mathcal A}_\ell|^2$.  The remaining linear
+vacuum sector has two transverse polarizations.  A parity-odd term proportional
+to $\boldsymbol{\mathcal E}_\ell\cdot\boldsymbol{\mathcal B}_\ell$, nonlinear
+terms, higher derivatives, and source couplings are deliberately excluded from
+the minimal parity-even action and belong to later research stages.
+
+\subsubsection{Relation to the existing continuum radiation bridge}
+
+The existing field $\mathbf A_{\rm eff}$ may be treated as a field-rescaled
+representative of the continuum link connection,
+\begin{align}
+    \mathbf A_{\rm eff}
+    =
+    \Lambda_\ell\boldsymbol{\mathcal A}_\ell.
+\end{align}
+In radiation gauge this gives the identifications
+\begin{align}
+    \rhoF
+    =
+    \frac{\epsilon_\ell}{\Lambda_\ell^2},
+    \qquad
+    K_\gamma
+    =
+    \frac{\mu_\ell^{-1}}{\Lambda_\ell^2},
+    \qquad
+    \frac{K_\gamma}{\rhoF}
+    =
+    \frac{1}{\epsilon_\ell\mu_\ell}
+    =c_T^2.
+    \label{eq:rt_link_to_Aeff_normalization}
+\end{align}
+The speed is invariant under the field normalization $\Lambda_\ell$.  Therefore
+the current quadratic continuum bridge need not be discarded; it is supplied
+with a microscopic relational interpretation.
+
+\subsubsection{Energy, flux, and link momentum}
+
+The positive quadratic energy density and energy flux are
+\begin{align}
+    u_\ell
+    &=
+    \frac12
+    \left(
+        \epsilon_\ell|\boldsymbol{\mathcal E}_\ell|^2
+        +
+        \mu_\ell^{-1}|\boldsymbol{\mathcal B}_\ell|^2
+    \right),
+    \\
+    \mathbf S_\ell
+    &=
+    \boldsymbol{\mathcal E}_\ell
+    \times
+    \boldsymbol{\mathcal H}_\ell,
+    \qquad
+    \partial_Tu_\ell+\nabla\cdot\mathbf S_\ell=0.
+    \label{eq:rt_link_energy_flux}
+\end{align}
+The associated momentum density in the isotropic linear branch is
+\begin{align}
+    \mathbf g_\ell
+    =
+    \frac{\mathbf S_\ell}{c_T^2}
+    =
+    \boldsymbol{\mathcal D}_\ell
+    \times
+    \boldsymbol{\mathcal B}_\ell.
+    \label{eq:rt_link_momentum_density}
+\end{align}
+These quantities reside in the link field.  They do not require nonzero net
+material angular momentum of the endpoint sites.
+
+\subsubsection{Helmholtz-sector separation}
+
+At leading vacuum order the total action is required to separate as
+\begin{align}
+    S^{(0)}
+    =
+    S_{\rm Euler}[\mathbf v,p]
+    +
+    S_{\rm link}[\vartheta,\phi].
+    \label{eq:rt_link_euler_factorization}
+\end{align}
+The material vorticity
+\begin{align}
+    \boldsymbol\zeta=\nabla\times\mathbf v
+\end{align}
+is not the link curvature
+$\boldsymbol{\mathcal B}_\ell$.  Ordinary source-free link propagation must
+therefore satisfy
+\begin{align}
+    \Delta\Gamma_C=0
+\end{align}
+for every unaffected material loop $C(T)$ and must leave the site sector label
+``rotating'' versus ``nonrotating'' unchanged.  Any later matter--link coupling
+must preserve this gate except at an explicitly declared source, boundary,
+reconnection, singularity, or Kairos event.
+
+A gauge-invariant source extension may later be written schematically as
+\begin{align}
+    \mathcal L_{\rm src}
+    =
+    \mathbf J_\ell\cdot\boldsymbol{\mathcal A}_\ell
+    -
+    q_\ell\Phi_\ell,
+    \qquad
+    \partial_Tq_\ell+\nabla\cdot\mathbf J_\ell=0,
+    \label{eq:rt_link_source_extension}
+\end{align}
+but neither $q_\ell$ nor its normalization is identified with the elementary
+charge at this stage.
+
+\subsubsection{Zero-legacy dimensional closure}
+
+If the only dimensional microscopic inputs allowed for the link layer are a
+mass density $\rhoF$, a circulation scale $\Gamma_0$, and the link spacing
+$a_\ell$, dimensional analysis permits
+\begin{align}
+    I_\ell
+    &=
+    \iota_\ell\rhoF a_\ell^5,
+    \\
+    K_\ell
+    &=
+    \kappa_\ell\rhoF\Gamma_0^2a_\ell,
+    \label{eq:rt_link_zero_legacy_coefficients}
+\end{align}
+where $\iota_\ell$ and $\kappa_\ell$ are dimensionless microstructural response
+coefficients.  Equation~\eqref{eq:rt_link_emergent_speed} then becomes
+\begin{align}
+    \boxed{
+    c_T
+    =
+    \frac{\Gamma_0}{a_\ell}
+    \sqrt{\frac{\kappa_\ell}{\iota_\ell}}
+    }.
+    \label{eq:rt_link_zero_legacy_speed}
+\end{align}
+Using $\Gamma_0=2\pi r_c\vchar$ only after the circulation convention has been
+fixed gives the dimensionless relation
+\begin{align}
+    2\frac{\vchar}{c_T}
+    =
+    \frac{a_\ell}{\pi r_c}
+    \sqrt{\frac{\iota_\ell}{\kappa_\ell}}.
+    \label{eq:rt_link_alpha_route}
+\end{align}
+For the special identification $a_\ell=r_c$, the original SST kinematic target
+$\alpha=2\vchar/c_T$ reduces to
+\begin{align}
+    \alpha_{\rm SST}
+    =
+    \frac{1}{\pi}
+    \sqrt{\frac{\iota_\ell}{\kappa_\ell}}.
+    \label{eq:rt_link_alpha_response_ratio}
+\end{align}
+Equations~\eqref{eq:rt_link_zero_legacy_speed}--
+\eqref{eq:rt_link_alpha_response_ratio} use no electromagnetic or quantum
+constant as an algebraic input.  They become predictions only if $a_\ell$,
+$\iota_\ell$, and $\kappa_\ell$ are obtained from an independently specified
+microstructure rather than fitted to $c$ or $\alpha$.  Agreement with the
+historical capacitance/impedance identity would then be a closure test; the
+capacitance formula and its impedance rewriting are not two independent routes.
+
+\subsubsection{Required certification programme}
+
+The link-field hypothesis is not promoted beyond research-track status until all
+of the following are completed:
+\begin{enumerate}
+    \item specify the microscopic graph or continuum adjacency law without
+    choosing $a_\ell$ from a target value of $c$;
+    \item calculate $I_\ell$ from the quadratic energy cost of link twist rate
+    and $K_\ell$ from the quadratic energy cost of plaquette holonomy;
+    \item recover two transverse modes and no physical longitudinal radiative
+    mode after constraint reduction;
+    \item verify Eq.~\eqref{eq:rt_link_lattice_dispersion} and the isotropic
+    infrared limit under lattice rotation and refinement;
+    \item demonstrate positive energy, local energy flux, and stable evolution;
+    \item verify Helmholtz-sector preservation and zero residual material
+    vorticity after a source-free pulse passes;
+    \item determine whether the microscopic dynamics has an exact front-speed
+    cone or only an infrared group-velocity cone;
+    \item add conserved knot sources and derive the static force law without
+    inserting $e$, $\varepsilon_0$, or $\mu_0$;
+    \item compare the independently predicted $c_T$ and dimensionless coupling
+    ratios with experiment only after the above steps are frozen.
+\end{enumerate}
+
+\textbf{Falsifiers.}
+The minimal hypothesis fails if the link action produces a ghost or negative
+energy branch, a species- or direction-dependent infrared speed without a
+controlled symmetry-breaking mechanism, an unavoidable longitudinal photon
+mode, permanent generation of material vorticity by a source-free pulse, or a
+value of $c_T$ that can be matched only by reusing the observed value of $c$ in
+$I_\ell$, $K_\ell$, or $a_\ell$.
